[[File:Brooklyn Museum Front Entrance.jpg|thumbnail|right|Brooklyn Museum]]
[[File:Brooklyn Museum Art School faculty. Francis Cunningham ca. 1979.jpg|thumbnail|right|Francis Cunningham teaching at the Brooklyn Museum Art School, ca. 1979]]
The '''Brooklyn Museum Art School ''' (BMAS) was a non-degree-granting professional school that opened at the [[Brooklyn Museum]] in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]] in the summer of 1941. Prior to the creation of the BMAS, classes for amateur artists had been offered by the [[Brooklyn Institute of Arts and Sciences]] (BIAS), the Museum's parent organization. BIAS offered hands-on art classes dating back to 1841. The Brooklyn Museum Art School provided instruction for amateur artists as well until January 1985 when it was transferred to the [[Pratt Institute]]’s Continuing Education Division.<ref>{{cite web|title=Guide to the Records of the Brooklyn Museum Art School|url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/opencollection/assets/BMAS_final.pdf|publisher=Brooklyn Museum|accessdate=19 August 2014}}</ref>

==History==
The Brooklyn Museum Art School title was first used in the 1941-42 annual report from the Brooklyn Museum, remaining separate from the Brooklyn Museum's Education Department, which was directed towards children. During [[World War II]] the Brooklyn Museum Art School offered limited classes in painting, photography and drawing. In 1945 the artist [[Augustus Peck]] became director of the school and expanded its offerings. As a result of the [[GI Bill]] the BMAS had very stable income and funding, allowing many prominent artists to teach or lecture at the school. Artists included Augustus Peck, [[William Baziotes]], [[Max Beckmann]], [[Ben Shahn]], [[Raphael Soyer]], and [[Reuben Tam]]. At its peak, the Brooklyn Museum Art School had almost 400 applicants. This number suffered as more institutions began to offer accredited programs in the fine arts during the late 1950s. A Bachelor of Fine Arts program in conjunction with [[Long Island University]] was planned to begin in 1959, but never came to fruition due to lack of funding.<ref>{{cite web|title=Brooklyn Museum of Art finding aid|url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/opencollection/assets/BMAS_final.pdf|publisher=Brooklyn Museum|accessdate=19 August 2014}}</ref>

==Notable Instructors==
* [[Max Beckmann]] 
* [[John Ferren]]
* [[Robert Smithson]] 
* [[Donald Judd]]

