'''Heritage Microfilm, Inc.''' (est.1997) is a [[microform|preservation microfilm]] and microfilm digitization business located in [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sos.iowa.gov/search/business/(S(qerjzgzfwbv300b23c4rl13t))/summary.aspx |title=Heritage Microfilm, Inc. |author=Iowa Secretary of State |work=Business Entities |accessdate=2 May 2012}}</ref>

==History==
The company began in 1996 when the microfilm division of Cedar Rapids-based Crest Information Technologies was sold to Christopher Gill. The microfilm division was responsible at the time for preserving newspapers and for microfilming business documents.  The business document filming portion of the business was soon dropped in favor of the newspaper microfilming division. (Crest in 1999 sold the remaining portion of the company to [[Lason]].){{citation needed|date=May 2012}}

In 1999, Heritage Microfilm began digitizing newspaper microfilm and launched [[NewspaperARCHIVE.com]].  Soon after, it began creating smaller "branded" newspaper archive websites in collaboration with publishing partners.  The ''[[Syracuse Post-Standard]]'' and ''[[Stars and Stripes (newspaper)|Stars and Stripes]]'' are among its clients for both microfilm and digital archives.{{citation needed|date=May 2012}}

The firm works with [[ANSI]]/[[AIIM]] standards for preservation microfilming. It has a humidity and temperature-controlled storage facility.  It is a [[Kodak]] ImageGuard facility. One of its specializations is damaged microfilm recovery.  It has an Extek 3441 microfilm duplicator, which duplicates at low speeds to prevent damage to [[Redox]] or [[cellulose acetate film|Vinegar-Syndrome microfilm]]. It uses Kodak [[silver halide]] microfilm for master film and primary duplications.  It discontinued the use of [[vesicular film]] for duplications, due to the poor quality film available from distributors.  It claims to use Kodak BrownToner, a [[photographic print toning|polysulfide film treatment]], on every reel of silver-halide microfilm that they produce.{{citation needed|date=May 2012}}

==NewspaperARCHIVE==
{{About|the website NewspaperArchive.com|a list of newspaper archives|Wikipedia:List of online newspaper archives}}
[[Image:NA_LogoHorz_3X8.jpg|thumb|right]]
'''NewspaperArchive.com''' is a commercial online database of digitized newspapers, and claims to be the world's largest newspaper archive.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/ |title=Newspaperarchive.com |author=Heritage Archives Inc. |location=855 Wright Bros. Blvd., Cedar Rapids, Iowa |accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> The site was launched in 1999 by Heritage Microfilm.<ref name="About Us">{{cite web |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/about-us.aspx |title=About Us |author=Heritage Archives, Inc. |work=Newspaperarchive.com |accessdate=2 May 2012}}</ref>

{{As of|2008|6}}, NewspaperArchive said it provided full text search for 909 million articles on 85 million pages over 240 years that represented 2,875 publication titles in more than 748 cities. As of 2015, the product includes newspapers from Azerbaijan, Canada, China, Denmark, France, Germany, Ireland, Jamaica, Japan, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, South Africa, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan, the United Kingdom, the United States, the U.S. Virgin Islands, and Uzbekistan.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/world-newspapers/ |title=World Newspaper Archives – Newspaperarchive.com |author=Heritage Archives Inc. |location=855 Wright Bros. Blvd., Cedar Rapids, Iowa |accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=October 2015}}

Searches can be conducted by keyword, date, and location. Results are free, but access to the newspaper articles available to download in [[Portable Document Format|PDF format]] requires a subscription. Searching is available directly from newspaperarchive or via news.google.com/archivesearch.  The company says that it follows the [[Automated Content Access Protocol]] in which its clients have a say in what is available online. The digitized newspapers that are currently available and [[Optical character recognition|OCR]]'d represent a fraction of the 150 million pages of historical documents that [[Heritage Microfilm]] maintains in its microform archive. According to NewspaperArchive, it is microfilming 2.5 million pages of newspapers each month and has 180,000 reels of microfilm.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heritagearchives.org/CurrentClients.aspx |title=HeritageArchives.org |publisher=HeritageArchives.org |date=2005-06-27 |accessdate=2011-12-20 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111224062523/http://www.heritagearchives.org/CurrentClients.aspx |archivedate=2011-12-24 |df= }}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=October 2015}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/HtmlViewer.aspx?ctl=About|title=Our Mission|publisher=NewspaperArchive.com|accessdate=2009-07-01}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=October 2015}}

The resource has had its fair share of criticism.{{according to whom|date=October 2015}} A reviewer in 2004 observed that at the time the archive had some errors with year dates,<ref>{{cite journal |author=Barry Popik |year=2004 |title=Digital Historical Newspapers : A Review of the Powerful New Research Tools |journal=Journal of English Linguistics |volume=32 |publisher=Sage }}</ref> and in June 2014, The Iowa Attorney General’s Office opened an investigation after complaints about deceptive and misleading practices that include charging subscribers for involuntary donations to a charity.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jordan|first1=Erin|title=Cedar Rapids company under state review after complaints|url=http://thegazette.com/subject/news/cedar-rapids-company-under-state-review-after-complaints-20140622|accessdate=3 September 2014|publisher=Cedar Rapids Gazette|date=24 June 2014}}</ref> As of August 1, 2014, Newspaper Archive, Inc. had a rating of ''F'' from [[Better Business Bureau]].{{Relevance inline|date=October 2015}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbb.org/iowa/business-reviews/online-publications/newspaper-archive-in-cedar-rapids-ia-32006934|title=Newspaper Archive, Inc. – BBB Business Review|publisher=Better Business Bureau|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref>{{third-party inline|date=October 2015}}

NewspaperARCHIVE claims as of 30 June 2018 that it has online newspapers dating from 1607 worldwide and its index includes 9,829 newspapers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/ |title=NewspaperArchive® &#124; Genealogy & Family History Records |publisher=Newspaperarchive.com |date= |accessdate=2018-06-30}}</ref> The website's principal competitor is [[Ancestry.com#History#newspapers.com|newspapers.com]].

==Heritage Archives==
'''Heritage Archives, Inc.''' (est. 2009) is related company in [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa]], that specializes in [[microfilm]]ing of [[newspapers]] that was also founded by Christopher Gill.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heritagearchives.org |title=HeritageMicrofilm.com |author=Heritage Archives, Inc. |location=855 Wright Bros. Blvd. SW, Cedar Rapids, IA |accessdate=2 May 2012}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=October 2015}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sos.iowa.gov/search/business/(S(jb3ugn2nxxk2p145oxym3imd))/summary.aspx |title=Heritage Archives, Inc. |author=Iowa Secretary of State |work=Business Entities |accessdate=2 May 2012}}</ref>{{better source|date=October 2015}} Among its products is NewspaperARCHIVE.<ref name="About Us"/> Clients include the state of Florida<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.transparencyflorida.gov/DisbByVendorPmt.aspx?FY=12&Obj=511000&DisbDate=0000&BE=45400100&AC=101977&Fund=1000&FundType=&LI=2966&AmtType=O&Vend=HERITAGE+ARCHIVE%2C+INC&M= |work=Transparency Florida |author=State of Florida |date=2012 |title=2011-12 Payments by Vendor - Operational |accessdate=2 May 2012}}</ref>{{better source|date=October 2015}} and the Boston Public Library.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpl.org/electronic/alpha.asp |title=Online Database A - Z List |author=Boston Public Library |work=Electronic Resources |accessdate=2 May 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140626100244/http://www.bpl.org/electronic/alpha.asp |archivedate=26 June 2014 |df= }}</ref>{{better source|date=October 2015}} The filing with the state of Iowa also include a [[Doing business as|dba]] name of ''CONVERXION SA DE CV''.

==Criticism==
Some observers have expressed{{who|date=October 2015}} concern about the extent of involvement of a private commercial business with stewardship of historical resources otherwise assumed to be held in the [[Public trust doctrine|public trust]].{{POV statement|date=October 2015}} For example, "until 2002, the [[Library of Congress]] and the [[Center for Research Libraries]] regularly microfilmed the principal daily newspaper of Jamaica, ''The Gleaner''. ... In 2002 the [[Gleaner Company|Gleaner Publishing Company]] executed an agreement with Heritage Microfilm, Inc. giving to the for-profit firm exclusive rights to reformat and distribute ''The Gleaner'', in both microform and digital format. Because Heritage now holds exclusive digital rights the agreement effectively shifts control of back files ... to the commercial sector, where it is marketed primarily for genealogists and family history researchers."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ala.org/acrl/conferences/confsandpreconfs/national/05titleindex |title=Knowledge Biodiversity: The Perilous Economics of World News Heritage Materials |author=Bernard F. Reilly, Jr. |date=2005 |work=Association of College and Research Libraries, 2005 national conference |publisher=American Library Association |accessdate=2 May 2012}}</ref>

The [[Supreme Court of the United States|US Supreme Court]] addressed the issue of compensation of works by freelance writers whose work was copied by electronic databases in the case of ''[[New York Times Co. v. Tasini]]'' (2001).

