{{Infobox Government agency |agency_name = History Nebraska |logo = HN logo color lg.png |logo_width = |logo_caption = History Nebraska Logo (2018) |seal = |seal_width = |seal_caption = |formed = 1878 |preceding1 = Nebraska State Historical Society |preceding2 = |preceding3 = |jurisdiction = [[Nebraska|State of Nebraska]] |headquarters = 131 Centennial Mall North, [[Lincoln, Nebraska]] |employees = |budget = |chief1_name = Trevor Jones |chief1_position = Director and CEO |parent_agency = |website = [https://history.nebraska.gov/ History Nebraska (Official Site)] }}
'''History Nebraska''', formally the '''Nebraska State Historical Society''' is a [[Nebraska]] [[state agency]], founded in 1878 to ''"encourage historical research and inquiry, spread historical information ... and to embrace alike aboriginal and modern history."'' It was designated a state institution in 1883, and upgraded to a state agency in 1994. The agency rebranded and announced their name change to History Nebraska on April 30, 2018.
The agency's mission statement is: "[to] collect, preserve, and open to all, the histories we share."
== State Historic Sites == Facilities and operations of the society include:
{|class="wikitable sortable" style="width:100%" ! width="*" |'''Site name''' ! width="*" class="unsortable"|'''Image''' ! width="*" |'''Nearest city''' ! width="*" |'''County''' ! width="*" class="unsortable"|'''Remarks''' |-- || [[Chimney Rock National Historic Site|Chimney Rock]] || [[File:Chimney Rock NE.jpg|200px]] || [[Bayard, Nebraska|Bayard]] || [[Morrill County, Nebraska|Morrill]] || The formation served as a landmark along the [[Oregon Trail]], the [[California Trail]], and the [[Mormon Trail]] during the mid-19th century. The trails ran along the north side of the rock, which remains a visible landmark for modern travelers along [[U.S. Route 26]] and [[Nebraska Highway 92]]. |-- || [[Fort Robinson]] || [[File:Fort Robinson post HQ 2.jpg|200px]] || [[Crawford, Nebraska|Crawford]] || [[Dawes County, Nebraska|Dawes]] and [[Sioux County, Nebraska|Sioux]] || Former [[U.S. Army]] fort in the [[Pine Ridge (region)|Pine Ridge region]] of northwest Nebraska. Fort Robinson played a major role in the [[Sioux Wars]] from 1876 to 1890. The [[Battle of Warbonnet Creek]] took place nearby in July 1876. [[Crazy Horse]] surrendered here with his band on May 6, 1877. |-- || [[John G. Neihardt State Historic Site]] || [[File:Neihardt study from E.JPG|200px]] || [[Bancroft, Nebraska|Bancroft]] || [[Cuming County, Nebraska|Cuming]] || Features museum exhibits about Nebraska [[Poet Laureate]] [[John Neihardt]]. The one-room study that Neihardt used from 1911 through 1920 as the place where he wrote many of his works is preserved at the site, and also features the Sacred Hoop Prayer Garden, designed by Neihardt, and a library with materials about Neihardt's life and legacy. |-- || [[Museum of Nebraska History]] || [[File:Nebraska State Historical Society Building.jpg|200px]] || [[Lincoln, Nebraska|Lincoln]] || [[Lancaster County, Nebraska|Lancaster]]|| The Society's headquarters features a library and archives, and administration and the research and publications operations of the Society. Located on the campus of [[University of Nebraska–Lincoln]]. |-- || [[Neligh Mill|Neligh Mill State Historic Site]] || [[File:Neligh Mill.jpg|200px]] || [[Neligh, Nebraska|Neligh]] || [[Antelope County, Nebraska|Antelope]]|| Museum commemorating the importance of flour mills to Nebraska and the West as a whole. Exhibits relating to the operation of the mill and its history are located in the original warehouse from 1866, as well as the 1915 addition where the power plant was once housed. The Society has restored the mill's office building, which has original furnishings. It reconstructed the 1919 flume to the south. The remnants of the dam that collected water for the mill are still visible on the Elkhorn River nearby. |-- || [[George W. Norris House|Senator George Norris State Historic Site]] || [[File:George Norris House from SE 2.JPG|200px]] || [[McCook, Nebraska|McCook]] || [[Red Willow County, Nebraska|Red Willow]]|| Home of U.S. Senator [[George W. Norris]] (1862–1944), a Nebraska politician who championed the [[New Deal]] of the 1930s and the [[Rural Electrification Act]]. |-- || [[Thomas P. Kennard House]] || [[File:Thomas P. Kennard house from N 1.JPG|200px]] || [[Lincoln, Nebraska|Lincoln]] || [[Lancaster County, Nebraska|Lancaster]] || Built in 1869, the Italianate house belonged to Thomas P. Kennard, the first Secretary of State for Nebraska, and one of three men who picked the Lincoln site for the new state's capital in 1867. |-- || [[Willa Cather House]] ||[[File:Willa Cather house from NE 3.JPG|200px]] || [[Red Cloud, Nebraska|Red Cloud]] || [[Webster County, Nebraska|Webster]] || Built in 1878, it is the house where author Willa Cather (1873-1947) grew up. Cather's descriptions of frontier life in Nebraska were an important part of literary canon of the early 20th century. |-- |}
History Nebraska also operates the Gerald R. Ford Conservation Center in [[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]].
