{{Infobox court case |name = S v Mhlungu |court = [[Constitutional Court of South Africa]] |image = |imagesize = |imagelink = |imagealt = |caption = |full name = State v Mhlungu and Others |date decided = {{Start date|1995|6|8|df=y}} |citations = {{Cite SAFLII |year=1995 |court=ZACC |num=4 |parallelcite=1995 (3) SA 867 (CC), 1995 (7) BCLR 793 (CC)}} |transcripts = |judges = [[Arthur Chaskalson|Chaskalson]] [[President of the Constitutional Court of South Africa|P]], [[Lourens Ackermann|Ackermann]], [[John Didcott|Didcott]], [[Johann Kriegler|Kriegler]], [[Pius Langa|Langa]], [[Tholie Madala|Madala]], [[Ismail Mahomed|Mahomed]], [[Yvonne Mokgoro|Mokgoro]], [[Kate O'Regan|O'Regan]] & [[Albie Sachs|Sachs]] JJ, [[Sydney Kentridge|Kentridge]] [[acting (law)|AJ]] |number of judges = 11 |decision by = Mahomed |prior actions = Referral from [[Natal Provincial Division]] |appealed from = |appealed to = |subsequent actions = |related actions = |opinions = |keywords = |italic title = }} '''''S v Mhlungu and Others''''' is a decision of the [[Constitutional Court of South Africa]] in which the court interpreted a transitional provision in the [[Interim Constitution of South Africa]] relating to the handling of criminal cases that were pending when that constitution came into force on 27 April 1994. The ruling, handed down on 8 June 1995, held that such cases were subject to the [[human rights]] protections in Chapter 3 of the Interim Constitution despite a clause appearing to exclude them.
