[[Image:1883 Isle of Man guide Ward Lock cover.png|thumb|right|''Ward & Lock's Illustrated Guide to and Popular History of the Isle of Man'', 1883]]
'''Ward Lock travel guides''' or '''''Red Guides''''' (1870s&ndash;1970s) were tourist [[guide book]]s to the [[British Isles]] and continental Europe published by [[Ward Lock & Co|Ward, Lock & Co.]] of London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wardlockredguides.co.uk/ |title=Ward Lock & Co's Illustrated Guide Books for Collectors and Enthusiasts |location=UK |publisher=Runela |accessdate=31 August 2013 |deadurl=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051108040453/http://www.wardlockredguides.co.uk/ |archivedate=November 8, 2005 }}</ref> The firm proclaimed them "amusing and readable" and the "cheapest and most trustworthy guides."<ref name=advert1882>{{citation |title =Ward & Lock's Tourists' Pictorial Guide Books (advert) |work=The Athenaeum |date=3 June 1882 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=y802AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA713 }}</ref> To other readers the books were promotional and "rarely critical."<ref>{{Citation |publisher = Reaktion Books |isbn = 9781861892744 |title = Designing the Seaside: Architecture, Society and Nature |author = Fred Gray |publication-date = 2006}}</ref> Compared to similar late 19th century series such as [[Methuen & Co]].'s ''Little Guides'', the Ward Lock guides emphasized "travel practicalities."<ref name=readman2005>{{citation |title=The Place of the Past in English Culture c. 1890-1914 |author= Paul Readman |journal= Past & Present |number= 186 |year= 2005 |jstor=3600854 }}</ref>
